# 1 Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC)

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012143318.png)


Public subnet
VPC IP range and the routing

Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (Amazon VPC) helps you define and provision a virtual network in the AWS Cloud for your AWS resources, similar to a traditional network in a data center.
When you create an Amazon VPC, you must provide the following information:
• Region
• Name for your Amazon VPC
• IP address range for your Amazon VPC

When you create an Amazon VPC, it spans multiple Availability Zones in the Region you selected.

After you create a VPC, the next step is to create a subnet. A subnet is a smaller network inside an Amazon VPC, where you place your AWS resources. Routing can be configured so that subnets are internet-facing, or public, or non-internet-facing, or private. A variety of routing configurations can be used to determine resource reachability outside the VPC. The configurations are applied at the subnet level. In this way, subnets provide a way to bound resources that require a specific external routing configuration.

For high availability, create your public and private subnets in two different Availability Zone.

The purpose of a subnet is to locate resources to specific Availability Zone. Subnets provide bounding of resources for routes providing external access to the VPC or where there is a need to separate resources for security control.

## 1.2 CIDR Classless Inter-Domain Routing

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012143455.png)

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012143746.png)

Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) is a method of specifying a range of Internet Protocol (IP) addresses. When you create a VPC, you must specify a range of IPv4 addresses for the VPC as a CIDR block. This is the primary CIDR block for your VPC.
Specifying a range dictates how many IP addresses are available to you. You specify a range by including a forward slash (/) character and a number at the end of the IP address.

For example, if you add /24 to the IP address 192.168.1.0/24, the last number, 24, specifies that the first 24 bits of the IP address are fixed, and the last 8 bits are flexible, with a subnet mask of 255.255.255.0. AWS reserves five IP addresses in each subnet for the network address, router, Domain Name Service (DNS), future use, and broadcast address. This means that you have 251 available addresses in this range.

Keep in mind that the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) reserves the following for private internets:
• 10.x.x.x
• 172.16.x.x–172.31.x.x
• 192.168.x.x

When a company needs a globally unique address space, it must obtain the address from an internet registry. A company that requests IP addresses for its external connectivity will not be assigned addresses from the blocks reserved for IANA.

Resources 
• For more details about address allocation for private internets, visit https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1918.
• To learn more about CIDR, go to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classless_Inter-Domain_Routing.


## 1.3 Internet or remote network access 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012143811.png)


NAT gateway Network address translation

You connect to your Amazon VPC through the internet by way of an internet gateway. In some ways, this is similar to using a modem or broadband to connect to the internet from your home, but the internet gateway is designed to be highly available and scale seamlessly.

You can connect AWS resources in your private subnet to the internet through a network address translation (NAT) gateway and prevent the internet from connecting to the resources. A NAT gateway should be created in each Availability Zone, so if an AZ becomes unreachable, the resources in the remaining Availability Zones can still reach the internet. However, each NAT gateway is designed to be highly available within the context of its own Availability Zone.

How would you establish an encrypted virtual connection between your on-premises data center and your Amazon VPC? With a virtual private gateway. To establish this connection, you must do the following:
1. Create the virtual private gateway and attach it to your Amazon VPC. 
2. Create a customer gateway and connect it to your on-premises data center. 
3. Establish a VPN connection between your virtual private gateway and customer gateway.

To establish a secure physical connection between your on-premises data center and Amazon VPC, you can use AWS Direct Connect. AWS Direct Connect reduces network costs and increases bandwidth.

With Direct Connect, you create a virtual interface directly to your Amazon VPC. You connect your on-premises network to an AWS Direct Connect location over a standard Ethernet fiber-optic cable. The AWS Direct Connect location provides access to AWS in its associated Region.

# 2 Amazon VPC Routing 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012144532.png)

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012144539.png)

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012144544.png)

When you connect to your Amazon VPC, route tables control where the network traffic is directed.
Each subnet in your Amazon VPC is associated with a route table. You can associate multiple subnets with one route table, but you can’t associate multiple route tables with one subnet.

Each route in the route table has a destination and a target. The destination specifies the CIDR range for which traffic is intended, and the target specifies the path it should use to be routed to the destination. The source is usually the subnet.

For example, to grant your subnet access the internet through an internet gateway, with an ID of igw-12345, the destination will be 0.0.0.0/0 and the target will be igw-12345. A local route is always present and cannot be deleted. The 0.0.0.0/0 route applies to all traffic not captured by a specific route (the local route, in this case).

To connect resources in a private subnet to the internet through a NAT gateway, you must:
1. Create a NAT gateway with an Elastic IP address in the public subnet. 
2. Update the route table associated with your private subnet to point internet-bound traffic to the NAT gateway.
3. 
When you create your Amazon VPC, AWS creates and associates a main route table with your subnets. By default, the main and custom route tables allows traffic between all subnets in the VPC.

To customize your network traffic, add routes in the custom route table and associate the table with your subnets.
For more information about custom and main routing tables, visit: https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_Route_Tables.htm

# 3 Network access control lists and security groups 

## 3.1 Network access control lists


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012144708.png)

To securely control your subnets’ inbound and outbound network traffic, you use a virtual firewall called a network access control list (network ACL). A network ACL has separate inbound and outbound rules, and each rule can either allow or deny traffic. Network ACLs are stateless, which means that even though network traffic was allowed to enter the subnet with a rule, it still needs another rule for the outbound network traffic.

Your Amazon VPC comes with a default network ACL, which allows all inbound and outbound IPv4 and IPv6 (if applicable) traffic. If no custom network ACL is created for your subnets, they will use the default network ACL.

To customize network access to your subnets, create a custom network ACL. By default, the custom network ACL will deny all inbound and outbound network traffic until you add rules. You can associate multiple subnets to a network ACL. But a subnet can only be associated with one network ACL. If you associate a custom network ACL with a subnet that has an existing network ACL, the previous one with be replaced.
Resource 
• To learn more about network ACLs, visit https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/vpc-network-acls.html.

## 3.3 security groups 

![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012145114.png)


To securely control inbound and outbound network traffic in your Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (Amazon EC2) instances, use a virtual firewall called a security group. Security groups are stateful. Once network traffic is allowed to enter an Amazon EC2 instance, the security group will remember the session and automatically allow the return traffic, without the need to check additional outbound rules.

By default, a security group only allows outbound traffic. To allow inbound traffic, you must create inbound rules. The source of an inbound rule can be a security group ID, CIDR block, or IP address.

Resource 
• To learn more about security groups, visit https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/VPC_SecurityGroups.htm


![](image/Pasted%20image%2020231012145204.png)

As an additional security measure, you can enable host-based firewalls in your Amazon EC2 instances. Host-based firewalls are operating system firewalls. The firewalls include:
• Iptables 
• Windows Firewall 
• Third-party security software for additional functionality, such as deep packet inspection or network threat protection

Host-based security software works well with highly distributed and scalable applications architectures because network packet inspection is distributed across the entire software fleet.

To monitor the network traffic going to and from a network interface in your VPC, enable VPC Flow Logs. These logs capture network traffic information for a VPC, subnet, or network interface. For example, if a specific network traffic is not reaching an instance, you can view the logs and find the cause.

To secure your Amazon VPC, we recommend the following best practices:
• Use multiple Availability Zone deployments for high availability 
• Use network ACLs and security groups 
• Use IAM policies to control access 
• Use flow logs to capture information about network traffic going to and from network interfaces in your VPC

Resource 
• To learn more about VPC Flow Logs, visit https://docs.aws.amazon.com/vpc/latest/userguide/flow-logs.html.
